external_knowledge:
- 'Shining star' refers to the course with the highest revenue above the average revenue;
- 'Outshines its peers' means the course has a total revenue greater than the average revenue;
- 'Standing tall as the beacon of success' emphasizes that the course is the top performer.

- "Cumulative enrollments" refers to the running total of students enrolled as the list is ordered by enrollment count in descending order;
- "Total revenue" is calculated by summing the amounts paid for all registrations in a course, with any commas removed from the amount;
- "Average rating" is the mean rating given by students for the courses taught by each instructor.

- Course categories are derived from the course description, with 'Art' and 'Science' as specific categories and 'Other' as a catch-all;
- The total revenue for each category is calculated by summing the amounts paid for all courses in that category;
- The final output is the category with the highest total revenue.

- "Flowers blooming" refers to students enrolled in the course;
- "Blossoming" refers to the average rating of the course;
- "Visitors" refers to the number of students;
- "Revenue" refers to the total amount paid by the students.

- "blossoms most beautifully" refers to the course with the highest average rating;
- "received more than one piece of feedback" means the course has more than one feedback entry;
- "ranks highest in the hearts of students" means the course has the highest average rating.

- "sought-after" refers to courses with the highest enrollment;
- "stars in the night sky" is a metaphor for the most popular or highly regarded items in a collection;
- "drawing the most students to their academic journey" means having the highest number of students enrolled.
